<span id="freeTextContainer12135680548556885165">this is one of those age old cases of &apos;it&apos;s not you, it&apos;s me&apos; and i am a lil sad.<br/><br/>despite really enjoying the song of achilles last november, i found circe to be an underwhelming companion. yet, as i&apos;m sitting here, trying to write this review and find reasons as to why i left the book with an overwhelming ~eh~ feeling, i&apos;m realizing that there&apos;s nothing obviously wrong with it.<br/><br/>objectively, circe is a fine story, but for some reason (one i wish I could articulate) i struggled to focus on and rema</span>
  <span id="freeText12135680548556885165" style="display:none">this is one of those age old cases of 'it's not you, it's me' and i am a lil sad.<br /><br />despite really enjoying the song of achilles last november, i found circe to be an underwhelming companion. yet, as i'm sitting here, trying to write this review and find reasons as to why i left the book with an overwhelming ~eh~ feeling, i'm realizing that there's nothing obviously wrong with it.<br /><br />objectively, circe is a fine story, but for some reason (one i wish I could articulate) i struggled to focus on and remain invested in the plot &amp; characters. with that being said, in spite of my low rating, i'm not trying to roast your fave or dissuade you from reading this one...especially since i have no valid criticisms to give. it just didn't gel with me, and sometimes that's all there is to it.</span>
